{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507233"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:50:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:50:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2613"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2613"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.01,0.46,0.16,0.34]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54263"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2613"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39763"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"2001"},{"type":"tags","id":"2516"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3582"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43194"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54263"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old lawyer presents to his general practitioner to discuss smoking cessation. He currently smokes 30 cigarettes a day and has done so since he was 17. He has decided to quit following a recent diagnosis of mild chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). He has tried previously to quit \u0027cold turkey\u0027 with no sustained success.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history is otherwise unremarkable and he denies a history of previous psychiatric illness, seizures, stroke or myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to behavioural support, which one of the following medications would be the most effective to singularly assist his smoking cessation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nicotine containing e-cigarettes","Nortriptyline","Nicotine patch","Buproprion","Varenicline"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBehavioural counselling is the cornerstone of smoking cessation and should be encouraged in all patients with the ASSIST-Lite tool for history-taking. In addition to this, in the absence of contraindications, pharmacotherapy should also be offered to all patients with nicotine dependence to increase chances of successfully quitting.  Whilst nicotine replacement therapy and bupropion are also excellent first-line medications, the most effective singular drug therapy intervention is vareniciline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENicotine replacement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (NRT) is a safe and effective aid to behavioural support. It is available in a number of forms, notably oral and patch forms. It should be used with caution with patients who have a recent myocardial infarction, unstable angina, severe arrhythmias or recent cerebrovascular event; however, it is safe to use in stable cardiovascular disease. The use of \u003Cstrong\u003Enicotine e-cigarettes\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for smoking cessation. In terms of efficacy, only combined NRT (for example a patch plus a short-acting form such as gum or lozenge) is considered to be an effective first-line alternative to varenicline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVarenicline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most effective, single-form pharmacotherapy when used in combination with behavioural support, and has been shown to more than double the chances of long term cessation. It is a nicotinic receptor partial agonist that relieves symptoms of craving and withdrawal. It is contraindicated in patients who are breastfeeding and pregnant. Varenicline has been associated with mood changes, depression, behavioural and sleep disturbance, abnormal dreams and suicidal ideation, however, no causal link has been established and it is safe to use in patients with stable mental illness, although monitoring should occur. For people with a creatinine clearance of less than 30 mL/min, start with varenicline 0.5 mg daily for 3 days and then a maximum of 1 mg daily. Avoid varenicline in patients with end-stage kidney disease (eTG).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBuproprion\u003C/strong\u003E was originally developed for use as an antidepressant, it significantly increases cessation rates, however is less effective than varenicline. It carries a risk of lowering the seizure threshold and thus is contraindicated in patients with a history of seizures, eating disorders and those taking monoamine oxidase inhibitors; while caution should be taken with other medications that may lower the seizure threshold.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENortriptyline\u003C/strong\u003E is a tricyclic antidepressant that is second-line pharmacotherapy for smoking cessation. It is not registered for smoking cessation in Australia due to the adverse effects of tricyclic antidepressants as well as the danger of overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Varenicline is the most effective single-form pharmacotherapy for smoking cessation when combined with behavioural support"],"references":["The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Supporting smoking cessation: A guide for health professionals. 2nd edn. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP, 2019.","\u0022Smoking cessation\u0022, Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines (eTG), March 2021 edition."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39763"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2613"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39763"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-02T12:55:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-02T12:56:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2613"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54263"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":